files.name: ndk/sdk_service.proto
files.description: Network programming APIs and messages. This is the base layer for agent registration, router event notifications such as interface, LLDP, BFD, and so on; also provides keepalive functionality to detect agent liveliness

enums.name: Operation
enums.description: Represents notification stream subscription request operation.

values.name: DeleteSubscription
values.description: Delete one subscription from existing subscriptions

messages.name: AgentRegistrationRequest
messages.description: Represents registration request message used in agent register and unregister.

fields.name: js_path
fields.description:
Optional, JSON path formatted strings, which are used in telemetry. Format of js_path follows hierarchical YANG. for example:
.interface{.name==*}.my_app.
.my_app.tunnel{.name==*}
'*'' needs to be replaced with a specific key.
fields.label: repeated

fields.name: agent_liveliness
fields.description:
Kill this agent unless a keepalive is received within this many seconds.  Value of 0
means do not monitor this agent for liveliness.

messages.name: AgentRegistrationResponse
messages.description: Represents registration response in reply to registration request.

fields.name: status
fields.description: Status of the register; for example: kOk, kFailed

fields.name: app_id
fields.description: Application ID assigned by SDK manager.

messages.name: AppIdRequest
messages.description: Represents application identifier request from agent. All applications are assigned an identifier by IDB.

messages.name: AppIdResponse
messages.description: Represents application identifier response to agent.

fields.name: status
fields.description: Status of the call; for example, kOk, kFailed

fields.name: id
fields.description: Identifier for the given application name

messages.name: KeepAliveRequest
messages.description: Represents keep alive request from agent to refresh liveliness of the agent.

fields.name: status
fields.description: Status of keepalive; for example, kOk or kFailed

messages.name: NotificationQueryRequest
messages.description: Represents notification query to return specific subscription details.

messages.name: NotificationRegisterRequest
messages.description: Represents notification request from agent. Agent uses this message to subscribe to router events such as interface create, delete, or update, as well as LLDP neighbor create, delete, or update, and so on.

fields.name: op
fields.description: Specific operation in the notification register request

fields.name: sub_id
fields.description: Set for delete subscription, unset otherwise

fields.name: stream_id
fields.description:
Stream identifier. This needs to be passed to the SDK manager for further notification
subscription changes specific to the current subscription

fields.name: sub_id
fields.description: Subscription identifier. Each subscription gets an identifier, which can be used to delete a subscription

messages.name: NotificationStreamResponse
messages.description: Represents notification stream response that contains one or more notification.

services.name: SdkMgrService
services.description: Represents base service that defines agent registration, unregistration, notification subscriptions, and keepalive messages.

methods.name: NotificationQuery
methods.description: Returns current or specific notification subscription details

methods.name: GetAppId
methods.description: Get application name from application identifier

methods.name: NotificationStream
methods.description: Send stream of event notifications based on the agent subscriptions

Uses variable-length encoding. Inefficient for encoding negative numbers  if your field is likely to have negative values, use sint64 instead.
Uses variable-length encoding. Signed int value. These more efficiently encode negative numbers than regular int32s.
Uses variable-length encoding. Signed int value. These more efficiently encode negative numbers than regular int64s.
Always four bytes. More efficient than uint32 if values are often greater than 2^28.
Always eight bytes. More efficient than uint64 if values are often greater than 2^56.
